---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Writing the PRD" description="Generate the PRD for DeskHub with a permissions matrix covering every feature and role.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Writing the PRD</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same flow — prompt plus template plus client brief, generate with Claude (the chat interface), review, iterate. You've done this twice. The guidance here is briefer.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">The new emphasis: the PRD must include a <strong class="text-text">permissions matrix</strong>. Without it, you can't verify access controls during implementation.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4">The prompt</h2>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here is a client brief for a co-working space management system called DeskHub:

[Paste Priya's brief here]

The system has three roles: Member, Admin, and Owner. Each role has different permissions.

Using the following PRD template, generate a complete Product Requirements Document. Include:
1. A permissions matrix showing every feature and which roles can access it
2. Specific acceptance criteria for every requirement — each one must be verifiable
3. An anti-scope section listing things that should NOT be built
4. Error handling for authentication failures (wrong password, expired token, locked account)
5. What happens when a user tries to access something they don't have permission for

Important: Admin creates member accounts. There is no public registration or self-signup. Members pay by invoice — no payment processing in the app.

[Paste PRD template here]`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The permissions matrix</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the most important artifact in the PRD. A table showing every feature and which role can access it. If this is wrong, everything downstream is wrong.</p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Feature</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Member</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Admin</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Owner</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Book a desk or room</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">View own bookings</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">View all bookings</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Manage members (create, edit, deactivate)</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">View revenue reports</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">View occupancy data</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Cancel own booking</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Cancel any booking</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Configure rooms and pricing</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">No</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Update own profile</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">AI will generate a matrix. Your review job: does it cover <strong class="text-text">every</strong> feature? Are there any features where the access level is ambiguous? Every ambiguity is a potential security hole.</p>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Watch for AI adding public registration.</strong> Priya said admin creates accounts. No self-signup. AI will almost certainly add a registration page — it's the default pattern for any app with login. Remove it. Also watch for AI giving admins access to revenue data — Priya was clear that only she sees financials.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Other review checks</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Authentication flows:</strong> Login, logout, password reset, token expiry — are they all specified?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Denied access behaviour:</strong> What does a member see if they try to navigate to /admin? A redirect? A 403 page?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Data isolation:</strong> The PRD should explicitly state that members cannot see other members' bookings or profiles</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Anti-scope:</strong> No payment processing, no public registration, no messaging, no mobile app, no calendar integration</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Save your PRD.</strong> The permissions matrix is the single most important reference for implementation and testing. You'll check every feature against it.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: access control patterns</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">RBAC is one way to model permissions. Here's what else exists and when each pattern fits.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">RBAC (Role-Based Access Control)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. Permissions assigned to roles (member, admin, owner), users assigned to roles. Simple, predictable, works well when roles map cleanly to responsibilities.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">ABAC (Attribute-Based Access Control)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Permissions based on attributes of the user, resource, and environment. "A user in the Sydney office can access APAC data during business hours." More flexible than RBAC, more complex to implement.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">ACL (Access Control Lists)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Permissions attached directly to resources. "This document is readable by Alice and editable by Bob." Common in file systems and document management. Fine-grained but hard to manage at scale.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">OAuth scopes</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Permissions granted to third-party applications. "This app can read your email but not send email." Used when your app integrates with external services (Google, GitHub).</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">PBAC (Policy-Based Access Control)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Permissions defined as policies in a separate engine (e.g., Open Policy Agent). Centralises access logic across multiple services. Used in microservice architectures.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">RBAC is the right choice for DeskHub — three distinct roles with clear boundaries. ABAC and PBAC add flexibility for more complex permission models, but the complexity isn't justified here.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: design</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">PRD is done. Now design three different dashboard views.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/5/design"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Design →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
